    <stitle>DOUBLE DIAPHRAGM ANCHORLOK SPRING BRAKE - CAGING SPRING</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec id="hl0401901">
        <title>CAGING SPRING</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Do not attempt to release (cage) the spring brake when the spring brake shows structural
                        damage. Caging the spring may result in the forceful release of the spring chamber and its
                        contents which could cause death, severe personal injury and/or property damage. Remove complete
                        spring brake chamber and replace with new unit.
                    </para>
                </warning>
                <warning>
                    <para>DISARM the spring chamber before discarding. Failure to disarm assembly prior to disposal may
                        in time result in spontaneous release of the spring chamber and its contents, causing death,
                        personal injury and/or property damage. Refer to
                        <hotlnk document="s04019_HL0401902.xml" xrefid="hl0401902">SAFETY CHAMBER</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="3">
            <title>WITH AIR PRESSURE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove dust plug from release tool keyhole in center of spring chamber (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401906">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401906" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401906" filename="../figg04/G0401906.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6. Mounting Release Tool</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. RELEASE STUD</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. DUST PLUG</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. WASHER AND NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. SIDE POCKET</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove release tool assembly from side pocket (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401906">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert release stud through keyhole in chamber into the pressure plate (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401906">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Turn release stud 1/4 turn clockwise.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pull on release stud to seat release stud crosspin in crosspin area of the compression
                    spring pressure plate.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Assemble release stud washer and nut on release stud finger tight (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401907">Figure 7</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401907" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401907" filename="../figg04/G0401907.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 7. Caging Spring</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. SERVICE BRAKE DIAPHRAGM</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. ADAPTER RETURN SPRING</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. COMPRESSION SPRING</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. RELEASE STUD</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. WASHER AND NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. SPRING BRAKE CHAMBER DIAPHRAGM</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. COMPRESSION SPRING PRESSURE PLATE</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. SERVICE RETURN SPRING</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. ADAPTER</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To ensure compression spring is fully caged, the stud length beyond the nut (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401908">Figure 8</hotlnk>) should measure:
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>36 Type Chamber = 3.38" Minimum</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>30 Type Chamber = 2.875" Minimum</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>24 Type Chamber = 2.915" Minimum</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1"></para>
                <figure id="f0401908" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401908" filename="../figg04/G0401908.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 8. "X" Dimension</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>The below listed instructions only apply when the spring brake is not pressurized. If air
                            pressure is used to compress the spring, do not tighten release stud nut more than finger
                            tight. Torquing the nut can cause pressure plate damage resulting in sudden release of the
                            spring causing death or severe personal injury.
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
